{% set basicRpCode %}<ruby>
  漢字 <rp>(</rp><rt>かんじ</rt><rp>)</rp>
</ruby>{% endset %}

{% set multipleRpCode %}<ruby>
  東 <rp>(</rp><rt>とう</rt><rp>)</rp>
  京 <rp>(</rp><rt>きょう</rt><rp>)</rp>
</ruby>{% endset %}

{% set withoutRpCode %}<!-- Without rp — no fallback -->
<ruby>漢字 <rt>かんじ</rt></ruby>
<!-- Renders as: 漢字かんじ (confusing!) -->

<!-- With rp — proper fallback -->
<ruby>漢字 <rp>(</rp><rt>かんじ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>
<!-- Renders as: 漢字(かんじ) (clear!) -->{% endset %}

{% set bracketRpCode %}<ruby>
  日本 <rp>[</rp><rt>にほん</rt><rp>]</rp>
</ruby>{% endset %}

{% set rpCssCode %}rp {
  display: none;  /* hidden in supporting browsers */
}{% endset %}

<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> element provides fallback text &mdash; typically parentheses &mdash; for browsers that do not support <a href="/docs/elements/native/ruby/">ruby</a> annotations. In browsers that support ruby, the content of <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> is hidden via <code>display: none</code>. In non-supporting environments, it displays, wrapping the annotation in parentheses.</p>
    <p>Always include <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> as a best practice to ensure graceful degradation.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Inside <a href="/docs/elements/native/ruby/"><code>&lt;ruby&gt;</code></a>, flanking each <a href="/docs/elements/native/rt/"><code>&lt;rt&gt;</code></a> element</li>
      <li>Any time you use ruby annotations and want graceful degradation</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Examples</h2>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/ruby-annotations.html" url="ruby-annotations.html" title="Ruby with rp fallback" shadow></browser-window>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Basic rp usage">{{ basicRpCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Multiple annotations">{{ multipleRpCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why Use rp?</h2>
    <p>Without <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code>, non-supporting browsers concatenate the annotation directly with the base text, making it unreadable:</p>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="With vs without rp">{{ withoutRpCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Alternative Characters</h2>
    <p>Any characters can be used instead of parentheses:</p>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Brackets instead of parentheses">{{ bracketRpCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CSS</h2>
    <code-block language="css" label="rp CSS">{{ rpCssCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>VB hides <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> via the browser default. The content is only visible in browsers without ruby support.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <p>In supporting browsers, <code>&lt;rp&gt;</code> content is typically hidden from screen readers. In non-supporting environments, the parentheses help clarify that the enclosed text is an annotation.</p>
  </section>

